    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-05-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-05-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="95"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d95">
                <head>95. National Security Study Memorandum 59<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d95fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                            >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, Box 365, Subject Files, <gloss target="#t_NSSM1"
                            >NSSM</gloss>s, Nos. 43–103. Secret. A copy was sent to General
                            <persName corresp="#p_WEG1">Wheeler</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1969-05-28">May 28, 1969</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <item>TO <list>
                            <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                            <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                            <item>The Director of Central Intelligence</item>
                            <item>The Special Assistant to the President for Science and
                                Technology</item>
                            <item>The Director, United States Arms Control and Disarmament
                                Agency</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <item>SUBJECT <list>
                            <item>
                                <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> Policy on Chemical and
                                Biological Warfare and Agents</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has directed a study of <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> policy,
                    programs and operational concepts with regards to both chemical and biological
                    warfare and agents.<note n="2" xml:id="d95fn2">On April 30, <persName
                            corresp="#p_LMR1">Laird</persName> expressed his increasing concern to
                            <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry Kissinger</persName> “about the
                        structure of our chemical and biological warfare programs, our national
                        policy relating to such programs, and our public posture vis-à-vis chemical
                        and biological warfare activities.” <persName corresp="#p_LMR1"
                            >Laird</persName> requested immediate <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> consideration of the matter. (Ford Library, <persName
                            corresp="#p_LMR1">Laird</persName> Papers, Box 3, Chemical Warfare and
                        Biological Research) <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>
                        replied on May 9 that he shared <persName corresp="#p_LMR1"
                        >Laird</persName>’s concerns. (National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 310, Subject Files, Chemical and
                        Biological Warfare, Vol. I) In a May 23 memorandum, <persName
                            corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> advised <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> to authorize a <gloss
                            target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> on the matter. “In the light of the
                        uncertainty surrounding <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> policy and
                        programs in this area, and in light of the increasing public concern and
                        attention being given the subject,” <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                            >Kissinger</persName> believed “that an overall study of present policy
                        and possible alternatives is required.” (Ibid., <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Institutional Files (H-Files), Box H–153, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 59)</note>
                </p>
                <p>The study should examine present <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> policy and
                    programs on <gloss target="#t_CBW1">CBW</gloss>, the main issues confronting
                    that policy, and the range of possible alternatives thereto. The analysis should
                    delineate (1) the nature of the threat to the <gloss target="#t_US1"
                        >U.S.</gloss> and its Allies and possible alternative approaches in meeting
                    this threat; (2) the utility of and circumstances for possible employment of
                    chemical and biological agents, both lethal and incapacitating; <pb facs="0343"
                        n="314" xml:id="pg_314"/> (3) the operational concepts relating to possible
                    use, testing and stockpiling; (4) the research and development objectives; (5)
                    the nature of and alternative approaches to the distinction between lethal and
                    non-lethal chemical and biological agents, including a review of current
                    applications of <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> policy relating to
                    non-lethal agents such as chemical riot control agents and chemical defoliants;
                    and (6) the <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> position on arms control,
                    including the question of the ratification of the Geneva Protocol of 1925.</p>
                <p>The study should include consideration of the effects upon <gloss target="#t_US1"
                        >U.S.</gloss> international posture in general and upon relationships with
                    Allies in particular; of the relevant legal questions; of the various cost
                    factors; and of the environmental control and public affairs aspects of <gloss
                        target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> policy.</p>
                <p>The President has directed that the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                    Political-Military Group perform this study and that the addressees be included
                    in the PMG for purposes of this study. The President has authorized the PMG to
                    establish the necessary subgroups for special or technical aspects of this
                    study.</p>
                <p>The report of this Group should be forwarded to the <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                        >NSC</gloss> Review Group by September 5, 1969.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Henry A. Kissinger</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
